"staff":false,"user_id":70704,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"1555's Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick/496532/1","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3565451,"name":"Simon Kozioziemski","username":"Simon6619","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/simon6619/{size}/251071_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-22T17:47:34.107Z","cooked":"<p>It seems like you need to add a loop into the method. I haven’t used this way of reading button presses before, so I wouldn’t know how to do it that way, but I can share our team’s way of doing it.</p>
<p>First we define the controller as an object:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">private final Joystick driver = new Joystick(0);
</code></pre>
<p>Next we make a variable for each button:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public final JoystickButton flipGyro = new JoystickButton(driver, 9);
</code></pre>
<p>Last, we use this button to do a command:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">zeroGyro.onTrue(new InstantCommand(() -&gt; s_Swerve.zeroGyro(0)));
</code></pre>
<p><code>onTrue</code> can also be swapped out for <code>whileTrue</code> depending on if you want the command to run once when the button is pressed (<code>onTrue</code>) or keep running and only get cancelled when the button is no longer being pressed(<code>whileTrue</code>).</p>
<p>Hope this helps!</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2025-03-22T17:47:34.107Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":45,"readers_count":44,"score":19.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":496532,"topic_slug":"button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick","display_username":"Simon Kozioziemski","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":70239,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick/496532/2","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3565475,"name":"Max Arnold","username":"Rice-Crispies-42","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/rice-crispies-42/{size}/242243_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-22T18:10:37.869Z","cooked":"<p>On another subject, how would you implement a slider as a speed control? my team wants a way to limit robot speed, and this throttle lever looks about right. It has an assignment of z in driverstation.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2025-03-22T18:10:37.869Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":29,"readers_count":28,"score":10.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":496532,"topic_slug":"button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick","display_username":"Max Arnold","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":70239,"username":"Simon6619","name":"Simon Kozioziemski","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/simon6619/{size}/251071_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":70704,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"1555's Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick/496532/3","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3565476,"name":"Max Arnold","username":"Rice-Crispies-42","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/rice-crispies-42/{size}/242243_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-22T18:10:59.437Z","cooked":"<p>Oh yeah, your button mapping worked</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2025-03-22T18:10:59.437Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":28,"readers_count":27,"score":5.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":496532,"topic_slug":"button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick","display_username":"Max Arnold","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":70239,"username":"Simon6619","name":"Simon Kozioziemski","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/simon6619/{size}/251071_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":70704,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"1555's Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick/496532/4","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3565491,"name":"Simon Kozioziemski","username":"Simon6619","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/simon6619/{size}/251071_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-22T18:47:00.400Z","cooked":"<p>I wrote some quick code that might work for this, but I’ll actually test it later.</p>
<p>First, I made a variable in my swerve subsystem that is the swerve multiplier:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public double swerveSpeed;
</code></pre>
<p>Next, I gave this multiplier a value in RobotContainer. I also made some logic that should ( hopefully ) make it slower as the slider goes up and make it so that when the slider is at the top, it’s the normal speed (my slider axis was 3, you can change yours).</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">        if(s_Swerve.swerveSpeed == 0){
            s_Swerve.swerveSpeed = 1;
        }
        else{
            s_Swerve.swerveSpeed = 0.5*(1+driver.getRawAxis(3));
        }
</code></pre>
<p>Finally, I simply multiplied the teleop swerve default command by this variable:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">       s_Swerve.setDefaultCommand(
            new TeleopSwerve(
                s_Swerve, 
                () -&gt; driver.getRawAxis(1)*(s_Swerve.swerveSpeed),
                () -&gt; driver.getRawAxis(0)*(s_Swerve.swerveSpeed), 
                () -&gt; -driver.getRawAxis(2)*(s_Swerve.swerveSpeed), 
                () -&gt; false
            )
        );
</code></pre>
<p>I’ll go test this on our robot today and let you know if it works or not.</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2025-03-22T18:47:00.400Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":25,"readers_count":24,"score":10.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":496532,"topic_slug":"button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick","display_username":"Simon Kozioziemski","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":70704,"username":"Rice-Crispies-42","name":"Max Arnold","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/rice-crispies-42/{size}/242243_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":70239,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/button-mapping-issues-on-flightstick/496532/5","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3565503,"name":"Max Arnold","username":"Rice-Crispies-42","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/rice-crispies-42/{size}/242243_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-22T19:23:55.627Z","cooked":"<p>This looks very promising, I’ll look at it after I finish debugging my joystick to stop binding my spin to the throttle, and instead map it to the twist.</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2025-03-22T19:23:55.627Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":21,"readers_count":20,"scor